Package uk.co.caprica.picam

Class Camera

  • java.lang.Object
    • uk.co.caprica.picam.Camera
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    AutoCloseable
    public final class Camera
extends Object
implements AutoCloseable
    Camera.

    Creating a camera instance will automatically "open" it so that it is ready for taking pictures.

    If an error occurs, or if you no longer need the camera instance, you should close() it.

    Using try-with-resources is recommended to make sure the camera instance is closed, for example: 

     try (Camera camera = new Camera(config) {
     camera.takePicture(new FilePictureCaptureHandler("capture.jpg"));
 }

    A closed camera can be reopened via open() if you are attempting to recover from an error, otherwise simply create a new camera instance.

    While the camera is in use you must make sure to keep references to the camera and any PictureCaptureHandler objects that you are using to prevent them from being garbage-collected. If you do not, a fatal crash may occur and kill your application.

    The underlying camera is a hardware resource and as such is fundamentally single-threaded. You must not access the camera from multiple threads concurrently.

    • Method Detail

      • open

        public boolean open()
        Open the camera, creating all of the necessary native resources.

        If the camera is already open this method will do nothing.

        Returns:
        true if the camera is open; false if it is not
        See Also:
        close()

      • takePicture

        public <T> T takePicture​(PictureCaptureHandler<T> pictureCaptureHandler)
                  throws CaptureFailedException
        Take a picture.

        The camera must be open before taking a picture.

        The capture handler will be invoked on a native callback thread.

        The calling application must make sure that the PictureCaptureHandler instance is kept in-scope and prevented from being garbage collected.

        Type Parameters:
        T - type that will be returned by the picture capture handler
        Parameters:
        pictureCaptureHandler - handler that will receive the picture capture data
        Returns:
        picture capture handler result
        Throws:
        CaptureFailedException - if an error occurs
        See Also:
        open(), takePicture(PictureCaptureHandler, int)

      • takePicture

        public <T> T takePicture​(PictureCaptureHandler<T> pictureCaptureHandler,
                         int delay)
                  throws CaptureFailedException
        Take a picture, with an initial capture delay.

        The camera must be open before taking a picture.

        The capture handler will be invoked on a native callback thread.

        The calling application must make sure that the PictureCaptureHandler instance is kept in-scope and prevented from being garbage collected.

        Type Parameters:
        T - type that will be returned by the picture capture handler
        Parameters:
        pictureCaptureHandler - handler that will receive the picture capture data
        delay - delay before taking the picture, specified in milliseconds
        Returns:
        picture capture handler result
        Throws:
        CaptureFailedException - if an error occurs
        See Also:
        open()

      • close

        public void close()
        Close the camera, freeing up all of the associated native resources.

        The camera can be reopened via open().

        If the camera is already closed this method will do nothing.

        Specified by:
        close in interface AutoCloseable
        See Also:
